<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-10-12T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-10-12T09:00:00-05:00" n="171" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d171">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">660p.11241/2: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Latvia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sussdorff</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Riga</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-10-12T16:00:00+02:00"><hi rend="italic">October 12,
                                        1928—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 12—11:20
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>87. Department’s 539, July 10th, last paragraph. Have received note from
                            Latvian Foreign Office stating as from October 15, 1928, United States
                            consular officers of career in Latvia shall enjoy on the basis of
                            reciprocity the privilege of free entry of personal property during
                            their incumbency. Please telegraph date on which similar privileges will
                            be accorded to Latvian consuls of career in the United States.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sussdorff</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>